The good, the bad and the ugly:  * Attentive staff! Our water glasses were never empty.  * Overpriced, average food. They also got my order wrong (TWICE) however, we were gifted a bottle of red wine for the inconvenience. The red wine was my favorite thing about the meal.  * The restaurant itself has strange evening lighting, warped wooden floors, and very little decor. Nothing  speaks Greek other than some lettering on the walls. Granted, we were shoved in the corner so I didn’t get a great look around.  * When I think Greek, I think FETA! My Greek side salad had no feta cheese. What? I asked for some on the side (which they quickly got for me) and honestly, it wasn’t all that great.  * Possibly one of the worst menus I have ever seen. It was not esthetically pleasing, it was hard to read and the entrees consisted mostly of fish, fish, and more fish.  I reserved a table at Kellari for our small group for 7 pm for dinner after a comedy show. We arrived on time to a relatively empty restaurant but were seated in the back corner next to the windows. The lighting was awful and it was a little chilly, making it hard to get comfortable. Not wanting to make a fuss and move, we stuck it out and snacked on what was set out on the table. There was a small basket of warm bread and a plate with hummus and olives. The bread was good but a strange pairing with the hummus. The hummus itself was lacking in flavor and unfortunately, set the tone for the rest of the meal.  We all ordered from the three course, pre-set meal options. The waitress informed us that two of the dessert options were not available, unusual but ok, not the end of the world. The guys got oysters for their appetizers which they enjoyed but did mention that they were on the small side. We got the spanakopita which was also good but room temperature, so kind of a let down.  The guys ordered the steak and potato entree which came out with our shrimp linguine. The shrimp linguine was actually a seafood medley dish with scallops and clams (not mentioned on the pre-set menu). I don’t eat scallops and clams so I sent it back. The bowl came back out extremely hot and still contained a scallop. So, they pulled out the other seafood, nuked it and returned it to me Still containing unwanted seafood...that’s unacceptable. What if I had an allergy of some sort?  We called for the head waiter to set things straight. I asked for just the shrimp and pasta, freshly made with no other seafood. He returned with a plate of shrimp (they were beautifully displayed and perfectly cooked) but No Pasta. I eventually got the linguine but wow, that was a 30 minute fiasco.  As I mentioned, the head waiter did gift us with a bottle of red wine so that was kind but man that linguine was bad. Literally, the worst pasta I have ever had in my life. The tomato based sauce was supposed to be spicy but it had no heat to it and no flavor. I’m not even sure if they added seasoning to it at all. The pasta itself was Way over cooked, not even close to al dente. Worse yet, there wasn’t any cheese. Where is the cheese in this restaurant? No, I like Really want to know.  Okay, so this was a realllllly long review, I know but I rarely write a bad review and I wanted to express my frustration about last night’s meal. We don’t get to go out often as parents and I wanted this to be a really good experience for all of us. The guys hated their steaks and my girlfriend was cold during dinner. Nobody walked away happy with their meal at Kellari.

Staff were running around taking dishes to the wrong tables and knocking into people. Everything was late coming out the kitchen, and short. One scallop for the 'scallops' dish. Shrimp and feta had no feta. Oysters Rockefeller needed more Rockefeller. Lamb was raw. Presentation was basic. At $320 for two with a bottle of wine, everything should be perfect. Won't be going back.

The food was really remarkable today. The negative reviews are surreal to me, but it seems they either get five stars or one, so I assume the folks who gave one star were probably just having a bad day.  I had to sit at the bar, I hadn't made a reservation. It didn't look full but often fancy schmancy places in DC do that, I'm used to it. The maître d' wasn't thrilled to see me, so I can see why some folks gave the restaurant less stars.  A couple of the waiters were slightly more nonchalant than Americans are used to, I overheard them slinging "Malakas" at each other, impossible to miss any time two Greek males are in a room together, which might explain the "European" service model.  Still, it wasn't too cold or too loud or anything that might make the ambiance unpleasant, and again, the food was just great. I had the Thalassina, and each part of the dish had a totally differentiated flavor. Very pleasant, and just about the right portion.
